[
  {
    "id": 1,
    "text": "Let's explore how the learning rate affects gradient descent on a parabolic loss curve.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 2,
    "text": "First, let's look at what happens when the learning rate is too high.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 3,
    "text": "With a high learning rate of 1.8, the algorithm overshoots the minimum and diverges, jumping wildly from side to side until it completely loses stability.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 4,
    "text": "Now, let's examine a learning rate that is too low.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 5,
    "text": "With a tiny learning rate of 0.08, gradient descent crawls painfully slow toward the minimum. It takes many more steps to converge, wasting computational resources.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 6,
    "text": "Finally, here's a well-chosen learning rate.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 7,
    "text": "With a balanced learning rate of 0.4, gradient descent smoothly converges to the minimum in just a few efficient steps, finding the optimal solution quickly and stably.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 8,
    "text": "Remember: too high causes overshooting and divergence, too low causes slow crawling, but just right achieves smooth convergence.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 9,
    "text": "Choose your learning rate wisely to optimize your machine learning models!",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  }
]
